title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith and Wesson, 1905, 4th, antique,  38 special.
postcontent: For Smith and Wesson lovers this is an early 1920s edition of the pre-model 10, sometimes called the model of 1905 hand ejector, it was made before SW started putting model numbers on them.  I grade it NRA 90% or better.  From the serial number it is below 400,000 which puts it around 1921.  It is called the the fourth revision.  It has the following patents on the barrel.  Oct.8, 01; Dec. 17, 01; Feb,8, 08;  Sep. 14, 08 and Dec 29, 14.   This gun has the diamond grips and a 5 inch barrel.  This gun has no rust or wear through the plating at all.  It is the best one I have ever seen, to be nearly 100 years old. From my research it was after they went from 38 Colt to the better steel which was heat treated, and has the 38 special marked on the right side of the barrel.  From my research it appears this gun was originally blue and nickeled sometime later.  The bore is perfect, shiny  and well pronounced lands and grooves.  The serial number is on the grip, barrel, cylinder and even on the ejector.   This gun has only been out of my safe once in 20 years and for several decades was carried by a senior citizen who carried it into his 90's. Just for reference, there is a dealer in Tulsa that specializes in these and he has several on Armslist, just type in 1905 in the search block.  He sells the nickel ones for $530 and the blue ones for $499.  From the pictures none is this good.
